\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 1. Product architecture\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 The three-tier hierarchy\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 The core data model is simple but the execution matters:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 Tier 1 \'97 Entity page
\f0\b0  (e.g. "Cardi B", "Philadelphia Phillies", "Kentucky Derby") This is a permanent, evergreen page. It has a bio/about section, a stats panel (total uploads, events covered, top contributors), and a chronological list of all events. Entities can be claimed/verified by the official rights holder down the road \'97 but they exist with or without official involvement. Think Wikipedia-style: fans create it, officials can enhance it.\

\f2\b Tier 2 \'97 Event page
\f0\b0  (e.g. "Cardi B \'97 Chase Center, San Francisco \'97 Oct 14 2025") Each event gets a unique, permanent URL. Key fields: artist/entity, venue, city, date, optional tour name. This page is the unit of organization \'97 every piece of media attaches here. Events can be pre-created (pulled from Ticketmaster/setlist.fm APIs before the event happens) so fans arrive at a page that already exists.\

\f2\b Tier 3 \'97 Media grid
\f0\b0  The browsable gallery of everything uploaded to that event. Supports photos and video. Sortable by: newest, most liked, "staff picks." Filterable by: photos only, videos only, section of venue (if you build that feature). Each media item has uploader credit, timestamp, optional caption.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 The upload flow\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 This is the make-or-break UX moment. It has to be nearly frictionless:\
