\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 4. The legal landscape\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This is real but manageable. Here's the actual picture:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 Fan photography rights
\f0\b0 : In the U.S., public photography and filming are largely protected under First Amendment rights, and venues reinforce this with ticket disclaimers and signage, legally framing attendance as consent. The practical reality is that fans film everything at concerts and sports events and nobody is prosecuted for it. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://fairpicture.org/stories/consent-by-ticket-rethinking-visual-privacy-in-the-age-of-virality/"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Fairpicture}}\

\f2\b Copyright ownership
\f0\b0 : The photographer (not the artist, venue, or promoter) owns the copyright in the photos they shoot. So fans uploading their own photos own those photos. Your platform is a host, not a rights holder. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cassels.com/insights/live-forever-ownership-and-usage-of-concert-photos/"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Cassels}}\

\f2\b Your platform's liability
\f0\b0 : The DMCA safe harbor protects you as a platform hosting user content, as long as you have a proper DMCA takedown process, don't have actual knowledge of infringement, and respond promptly to valid takedown requests. This is the same protection that covers YouTube, Instagram, and every other UGC platform. You're not in unusual legal territory here.\

\f2\b What you need in your ToS
\f0\b0 :\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Users warrant they own or have rights to what they upload\
\ls8\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Users grant the platform a license to display, distribute, and create thumbnails/previews\
\ls8\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Clear DMCA contact and process\
\ls8\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 No commercial use of others' uploads without explicit license\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 The one gray area
\f0\b0 : Some venues and artists explicitly prohibit video recording in their ticketing terms. Users violating those terms is a contractual issue between them and the venue \'97 it doesn't make your platform liable for hosting the content, assuming you have a good DMCA process. That said, a clear community guideline that users should follow venue rules, and a mechanism for venues to request takedowns of specific recordings, will help you maintain good relationships with the industry.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 5. Go-to-market strategy\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Cold start solution\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 The empty-page problem is real \'97 nobody uploads to a page with nothing on it. The fix is a two-pronged seeding strategy:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 Historical backfill
\f0\b0 : Use setlist.fm + Instagram/Twitter scraping (public hashtags like 
\f6\fs26 #beyonceconcert
\f0\fs24 , 
\f6\fs26 #2025WorldSeries
\f0\fs24 ) to seed pages with existing fan content that's already public. You're not hosting it \'97 you're embedding/linking. This creates the appearance of a live community on day one. Over time, original uploads replace embeds.\

\f2\b Partner early with 3-5 mid-tier artists or teams
\f0\b0  who have passionate fanbases and will promote the platform from their own channels. Not stadium-level acts (they have lawyers and IP concerns). Think: touring bands with 100k-500k followers, minor league sports teams, regional racing circuits. Their fans are hungry for community and not overprotected by label/league IP enforcers.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 Distribution\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 SEO is your primary acquisition channel.
\f0\b0  Every event page is a long-tail keyword that nobody is ranking for. "Taylor Swift Eras Tour Philadelphia night 2 fan photos" has search volume and zero strong results. You want to be the answer. This means clean URLs, proper metadata, structured data markup for events.\
\ls9\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Social seeding
\f0\b0 : Every photo/video uploaded should have a shareable card with your branding. When fans share their uploads to Instagram or TikTok, that's a distribution touchpoint.\
\ls9\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Ticket integrations
\f0\b0 : Eventually you want a Ticketmaster or SeatGeek API relationship where you can surface "see fan photos from this event" on the ticketing page. That's a moat.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 6. Monetization (in order of execution)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Phase 1 \'97 Free, build the network
\f0\b0  No monetization for the first 12-18 months. The goal is uploads, not revenue. Every dollar gate you add at this stage costs you 10x in growth.\

\f2\b Phase 2 \'97 Premium uploader tier ($5-10/month)
\f0\b0  Higher upload limits (free: 20 photos + 2 videos per event; premium: unlimited), HD video uploads, ability to mark uploads as "licensed" for others to request permission to use, early access to features. This is your first revenue line and it targets the power users who are already uploading a lot.\

\f2\b Phase 3 \'97 Official entity partnerships
\f0\b0  Teams, artists, and venues pay for a "verified" page experience: curated official content mixed in with fan uploads, custom branding on the page, ability to feature certain uploads, access to engagement analytics. Pricing: $500-2,000/month per entity, or a rev-share on licensed content. This is B2B SaaS on top of a consumer platform \'97 a proven playbook.\

\f2\b Phase 4 \'97 Content licensing marketplace
\f0\b0  Fans can list their uploads as available for licensing. Media outlets, brands, documentarians can request a license. Platform takes 20-30% of the transaction. This is where a single viral video from a historic event becomes real revenue for the uploader \'97 and a powerful word-of-mouth story for the platform.\

\f2\b Phase 5 \'97 Contextual advertising
\f0\b0  High-intent, low-friction. Someone browsing photos from a Phillies game is a perfect audience for stadium food delivery, sports merchandise, or the team's streaming package. CPMs on sports/entertainment UGC pages will be strong. Keep ads sparse and non-interruptive \'97 the community will revolt at banner-heavy pages.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 7. Competitive moat over time\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The business gets stronger as it scales in ways competitors can't easily replicate:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Data network effect
\f0\b0  \'97 every upload makes every page better. A competitor starting from zero can't replicate 3 years of fan uploads across 50,000 events.\
\ls10\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 SEO compounding
\f0\b0  \'97 each event page accumulates backlinks, organic traffic, and content over time. A 2019 World Series page keeps getting traffic forever.\
\ls10\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Uploader identity
\f0\b0  \'97 fans who've built a profile, accumulated likes, and established a reputation on your platform have real switching costs.\
\ls10\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 API relationships
\f0\b0  \'97 once you have partnerships with Ticketmaster, setlist.fm, or sports leagues, those are hard to displace.\
\ls10\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Archive positioning
\f0\b0  \'97 if you market yourself as "the fan's visual record of live events," you have a cultural mission that goes beyond just another photo app. That framing matters for press, for partnership conversations, and for user loyalty.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

