\cf0 This is what the viewer sees when they tap a song on the setlist. A few things worth noting in the design:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 The show timeline bar
\f0\b0  at the top shows where in the overall show this song fell. For a virtual attendee, this is orienting \'97 it tells them they're 18% into the show, not just floating in abstract clip space.\

\f2\b Sort modes
\f0\b0  are where the real UX power is. "Best angle" is the default algorithmic pick. "Floor / pit" and "Upper sections" let you choose your vantage point preference \'97 just like choosing your ticket. "Full song only" filters to clips where the uploader captured the entire song, not just a fragment. These are the kind of controls that make someone feel like they're genuinely navigating the show.\

\f2\b Confidence scores
\f0\b0  are visible but small \'97 they're for trust, not for feature. A 97% confidence auto-tag next to a manually tagged clip tells you both can be trusted. The 71% confidence clip is visually dimmed and flagged \'97 the viewer knows to take it with a grain of salt.\

\f2\b Song navigation
\f0\b0  at the bottom is essential. A virtual attendee is going to step through the whole setlist song by song, like chapters in a movie. Prev/next makes that feel intentional, not accidental.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 The edge cases worth solving early\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Songs not on setlist.fm yet.
\f0\b0  In the hours right after a show, the setlist might not be entered yet \'97 fans do this manually on setlist.fm, usually within a day. In the meantime, clips get tagged as "unconfirmed song" and are surfaced in a holding bucket. Once the setlist is confirmed and imported, all those clips get matched retroactively.\

\f2\b Surprise songs / covers.
\f0\b0  An artist plays a cover or a song not in their normal catalog. The fingerprint will still identify it (ACRCloud knows virtually every commercially released song), it just won't match anything on the imported setlist. These get flagged as "unlisted song" \'97 which is actually a feature, not a bug. Superfans love discovering that an artist played a rare cover, and your platform surfaces it automatically.\

\f2\b Instrumental sections, crowd chants, speeches.
\f0\b0  These don't fingerprint to a song. They go into an "untagged moments" bucket that can be browsed separately. Actually useful \'97 sometimes the between-song banter is more interesting than the songs.\

\f2\b Live versions that sound different.
\f0\b0  Some artists remix songs heavily live \'97 the live version might not fingerprint well against the studio recording. This is the hardest case. Mitigation: use timestamp cross-referencing. If 8 clips from this show all fingerprinted as "no match" but were uploaded within a 5-minute window, and the setlist shows a song at that time, you can infer they're probably from that song and offer that as a suggested tag to uploaders.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Why this is a real technical moat\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Here's the thing \'97 the fingerprinting API itself is a commodity. Anyone can call ACRCloud. The moat isn't the technology, it's the 
\f2\b combination of setlist data + fingerprinting + a crowd of uploaders tagging things + a correction layer + time.
\f0\b0  After two years of shows, you'll have a dataset of confirmed song-to-clip links that no one else has. That dataset trains your own confidence models, reduces your API costs as your local cache fills up, and becomes genuinely defensible.\
It also compounds in an unexpected way: once you have a critical mass of tagged clips per song, you can start answering questions no one else can. Which song in Taylor Swift's setlist generates the most fan video? Which moment of a show gets filmed the most? Which seat sections capture the best angles for specific songs? That's data that artists, tour managers, and venue operators would genuinely pay for \'97 and it falls out naturally from the tagging system you've already built.\
Want to go into the venue map feature, the Watch mode sequencing logic, or something else?\
