\f2\b \cf0 \strokec2 What CrowdAlbum actually proved\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 CrowdAlbum worked with more than 1,000 artists and venue partners before being acquired \'97 on only $100k raised and a tiny team. That's remarkable distribution for a bootstrapped startup. But here's the crucial detail: CrowdAlbum gathered photos and videos shared on Twitter and Instagram without fans needing to use hashtags, presumably using time and location data from social media posts. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://techcrunch.com/2016/04/27/spotify-buys-photo-aggregator-crowdalbum-to-build-more-marketing-tools-for-artists/"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 TechCrunch}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://fortune.com/2016/04/27/spotify-crowdalbum-acquisition"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Fortune}}\
Read that carefully. CrowdAlbum wasn't asking fans to upload 
\f7\i to
\f0\i0  their platform. It was 
\f2\b aggregating content fans had already posted elsewhere
\f0\b0 . The upload behavior it proved was "fans post concert content to Instagram and Twitter" \'97 which is undeniably true, but it's not the same as "fans will upload directly to a dedicated platform."\
That's an important distinction. It means CrowdAlbum sidstepped the cold-start upload problem entirely \'97 and also means it never actually tested whether fans would upload natively. Spotify bought it for the artist relationship tools and the data layer, not for a proven direct-upload product.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 What it does prove:
\f0\b0  Fan-generated concert content exists at massive scale on social platforms. The behavior is real. The content is there. The question is whether fans will redirect that behavior to you.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \strokec2 What SureShot and Happaning prove\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 These are B2B products \'97 SureShot is a Copenhagen-based startup building an AI-assisted crowd-generated video platform for event organizers. Organizers pay, set up an event, distribute a PIN, and collect fan uploads. They've proven that 
\f2\b when an organizer actively promotes a collection campaign at their event \'97 signage, announcements, incentives \'97 fans will upload directly to a platform.
\f0\b0  {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://sureshot.video/about"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 SureShot}}\
That's a stronger proof point than CrowdAlbum. But there's a catch: the organizer is doing real work to drive participation. Signage at the venue, announcements from the stage, sometimes prizes for best clip. The upload rate when an organizer is actively pushing it vs. organic discovery is likely 5-10x different.\
Your platform is more organic \'97 you're not relying on an organizer to push it. That's harder, but it's also how you scale without a B2B salesforce.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \strokec2 The underlying behavior data is actually very strong\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 This is where it gets genuinely encouraging. The data on fan filming and sharing behavior is extensive:\
56% of concert attendees engage on social media at a show \'97 including 74% of millennials \'97 with 33% sharing photos and 25% posting videos. That's Nielsen data from a large sample. At a 20,000-seat arena, that's roughly 5,000 people posting videos and 6,600 sharing photos during the show itself. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.billboard.com/pro/nielsen-releases-in-depth-statistics-live-music-behavior-360-report/"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Billboard}}\
Research on fan filming behavior found that fans selectively upload clips with the highest excitement \'97 songs with lots of screaming, group behaviors like chanting and cheering in unison. The clips often included songs with special meaning to the fandom. This is crucial \'97 fans aren't filming randomly. They're filming the moments they want to relive and share. That's exactly the content you want on your platform. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/21582440241293314?icid=int.sj-abstract.citing-articles.243"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Sage Journals}}\
On the demand side \'97 the people who couldn't attend: a Live Nation global study of 40,000 people found fans traveled 40 billion miles for concerts in 2024, with 93% saying they attend shows because they crave real experiences over virtual ones. That last number sounds like bad news for virtual attendance, but read it again \'97 93% of people 
\f7\i who attended
\f0\i0  prefer real. The question is about the much larger group who never got there. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.marketscreener.com/news/global-report-surveying-40-000-people-finds-live-music-is-the-world-s-favorite-form-of-entertainment-ce7d5fd9de88f220"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 marketscreener}}\
And that group is growing. The average ticket price for a concert in one of the top 100 global tours was $136 in 2024, up 50% from an average of $91 in 2019. One in five Gen Z concertgoers reported spending beyond their means to attend concerts in the past two years. The pricing pressure is real and structural \'97 it's not a temporary blip. More people are being priced out every year, and they're not losing interest in the music. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnbc.com/2026/05/23/concert-ticket-prices-live-music-demand.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 CNBC}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.billboard.com/pro/concert-ticket-prices-studies-spending-debt-consumer-trends/"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Billboard}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \strokec2 The one genuinely unproven thing\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Here's the honest gap in the validation stack:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 Nobody has proven that a non-attendee will spend 30+ minutes watching fan-shot concert footage on a dedicated platform.
\f0\b0 \
YouTube proves people watch concert footage \'97 but usually officially released content, or occasional viral clips. The closest analog is the "fancam" culture on Twitter/X and TikTok, where individual clips from concerts rack up millions of views. That proves demand for clips. But a sustained "virtual attendance" session \'97 working through a setlist, watching multiple angles, spending real time with an event \'97 that's an unproven behavior at platform scale.\
This is actually fine. It's a reasonable inference from strong adjacent signals, and you don't need to prove it before building the MVP. But it's the question your MVP should be designed to answer, not assumed.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

