\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 The short answer\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 You can seed pages with social content, but 
\f2\b how
\f0\b0  you do it matters enormously. There are three distinct approaches with very different legal profiles, and you should only pursue two of them.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 The three approaches, ranked by risk\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 1. Embed, don't host \'97 low risk 
\f8\b0 \uc0\u10003 
\f2\b \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 This is the approach that's cleanest legally and is also how most of the web works. Instead of downloading content and storing it on your servers, you embed it directly from the source platform using their official embed API.\
Instagram, TikTok, YouTube, and Twitter/X all provide official oEmbed endpoints. When you embed a post this way:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls22\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The media file never touches your servers\
\ls22\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The original creator's username and link are displayed automatically\
\ls22\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The platform's own infrastructure serves the content\
\ls22\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Instagram's own API documentation explicitly describes the oEmbed endpoint and states "you can get a public Instagram photo or video post's embed HTML code and use it to embed the post in other websites \'97 each embedded post gives proper attribution by displaying the post owner's username and linking to the post owner's profile." {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://natlawreview.com/article/to-embed-or-not-to-embed-new-challenge-to-embedding-images-social-media"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 NatLawReview}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The legal protection here comes from what courts call the "server test" \'97 infringement only occurs if a copy of the image is stored on the accused infringer's computer server or other storage device. Embedding via official APIs passes this test because you're not storing anything. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.millernash.com/industry-news/ninth-circuit-confirms-embedding-remains-fair-use"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Miller Nash LLP}}\
There is some ongoing legal murkiness \'97 a photographer petitioned the Supreme Court in 2025 to reconsider the server test \'97 and there's a circuit split, with the Second Circuit saying embedding can infringe and the Ninth saying it doesn't. But for a startup seeding content in the short term, embedding via official APIs is the pragmatic, defensible choice. Just be ready to pull embeds if a platform changes its policy or a creator requests removal. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.digitalcameraworld.com/tech/social-media/does-embedding-an-instagram-violate-copyright-a-photographer-wants-the-supreme-court-to-decide"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Digital Camera World}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ipandmedialaw.fkks.com/post/102heu2/instagram-strikes-again-users-can-now-disable-embedding"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Passle}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 What this looks like in practice:
\f0\b0  You search Instagram for 
\f6\fs26 #beyonceconcert #renaissancetour
\f0\fs24  and find 50 good fan posts. You pull the oEmbed code for each, attach them to the correct event page, and they display with full attribution. The fan sees their post featured on your platform, often likes it, and sometimes becomes an uploader themselves. That last part is actually a flywheel.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \strokec2 2. Aggregate public metadata + link out \'97 very low risk 
\f8\b0 \uc0\u10003 
\f2\b \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Even safer than embedding: don't display the content at all on your page. Instead, surface a feed of public posts with thumbnails and captions that link out to the original. Think of it as a curated directory, not a media host.\
"12 fans posted about this show on Instagram \'97 see them here 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 "\
This is essentially what Google Image Search does. The hiQ v. LinkedIn ruling established that scraping publicly available data on the web doesn't violate the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, and the 2024 Meta v. Bright Data ruling reaffirmed that scraping publicly available data remains legally defensible \'97 Meta lost because they couldn't prove Bright Data was scraping data behind login walls. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://scrapfly.io/blog/posts/social-media-scraping"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Scrapfly}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://scrapecreators.com/blog/is-web-scraping-legal-a-guide-based-on-recent-court-ruling"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Scrapecreators}}\
Linking out drives traffic to the original creator, which is genuinely good for them, builds goodwill, and keeps you firmly in the clear. The downside is a weaker on-page experience \'97 someone has to click away to see the content.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 This is also a good long-term partnership feature.
\f0\b0  "Your post was featured on [Platform] as a highlight from the Beyonc\'e9 show \'97 come upload your originals directly." That notification, sent via Instagram DM or tagged in a comment, converts social posters into direct uploaders.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \strokec2 3. Scrape and re-host \'97 high risk 
\f8\b0 \uc0\u10007 
\f2\b \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Downloading images and videos from social platforms and storing them on your own servers is where you get into real trouble, for two separate reasons:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 Copyright:
\f0\b0  The fan owns their photo or video. You don't have a license to copy and store it. The server test no longer protects you once the file is on your server. Even if the content is publicly visible, copying it is a different legal act than linking to it.\

\f2\b Platform ToS:
\f0\b0  Every major platform \'97 Instagram, TikTok, Twitter/X \'97 explicitly prohibits scraping content for re-hosting in their terms of service. LinkedIn's court victory over hiQ ultimately came down to contract-based ToS violations, not just the CFAA. Platforms have gotten more aggressive enforcing this, not less. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.socialmediatoday.com/news/LinkedIn-Wins-Latest-Court-Battle-Against-Data-Scraping/635938/"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Social Media Today}}\

\f2\b The Clearview AI cautionary tale:
\f0\b0  Clearview AI scraped billions of images from social media and in 2025 settled a class action lawsuit agreeing to pay approximately $51 million and award plaintiffs 23% of company equity. Obviously facial recognition is a different context, but it illustrates what scrape-and-store at scale looks like from a liability perspective. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.lection.app/blogs/hiq-labs-vs-linkedin-case-explained"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \ul \ulc6 \strokec6 Lection}}\
Don't do this. The risk-to-reward ratio is terrible for a startup that's trying to build partnerships with artists and venues.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 The smarter seeding strategy: a combination approach\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Here's how to think about it as a sequenced playbook:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa260\partightenfactor0

