\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 What Concert Archives actually is vs. what it looks like it should be\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 It's essentially a 
\f2\b concert attendance ledger
\f0\b0  \'97 fans log "I was there" the same way you'd log a book on Goodreads. The media is an afterthought bolted on later. The proof is in the UI: photos and videos are buried under a "Scroll to" nav, the concert list is a plain text table, and the whole thing looks like it was designed in 2013 and never meaningfully updated.\
The ads are the tell. Wine ads. Adobe Acrobat ads. YouTube TV ads. These are remnant network ads served to a site that never built a real monetization strategy \'97 which means they never built a real product strategy either.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 The five specific things these screenshots show you to do differently\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 1. Lead with media, not data.
\f0\b0  Concert Archives leads with a text list of shows. Every page should open with the best video from that venue or artist \'97 autoplay muted, full width. Make someone feel the show in 3 seconds before they read a word.\

\f2\b 2. Video is first class, not a tab.
\f0\b0  On Concert Archives, Videos is a navigation item you scroll to. On Showside, video is the default view. The Watch tab is the hero. Photos are secondary.\

\f2\b 3. Upload friction is clearly too high.
\f0\b0  The sparse media despite 7,475+ concerts at just one venue means people aren't uploading. Either the upload flow is too hard, there's no motivation to do it, or both. Your 60-second mobile upload experience is a direct fix to this.\

\f2\b 4. The attendee list is a missed opportunity.
\f0\b0  162 attendees at Rockwood but almost no media. Those 162 people were there \'97 they have photos on their phones right now. Concert Archives never connects the logged attendance to an upload prompt. You should: "You logged this show \'97 want to add your photos and video?"\

\f2\b 5. No non-attendee experience exists.
\f0\b0  There is nothing on Concert Archives for someone who wasn't there. It's entirely inward-facing \'97 a diary for people who attended. The entire virtual attendance angle, which is your primary audience, is completely absent. A non-attendee landing on that Roxy page sees a text list of band names and two videos from different years. There's nothing to watch, nothing to experience, nothing to come back for.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 What this means for your positioning\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Concert Archives accidentally answers a question nobody was really asking \'97 "how do I keep a log of concerts I've been to?" It's Letterboxd for concerts, except Letterboxd actually has a thriving community because movies have a broader audience and logging a film takes 10 seconds.\
You're answering a completely different and much larger question: 
\f2\b "I couldn't go to that show \'97 what was it like?"
\f0\b0 \
That's the reframe that makes everything click. Concert Archives is a diary. Showside is a broadcast. One is private memory management. The other is public entertainment. They happen to share some infrastructure \'97 event pages, media uploads \'97 but the product experience, the primary user, and the value proposition are fundamentally different.\
The fact that Concert Archives has been around since 2013, got press in the New York Times and Pitchfork, and still looks like this after 12 years is actually the most bullish signal you could find. The concept has been validated enough to survive for over a decade. The execution has never been good enough to make it matter. That's your opening.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

