\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 The way to think about it\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Rather than choosing one, think of it as 
\f2\b two views of the same underlying data:
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 The experience view
\f0\b0  \'97 "Taylor Swift live" \'97 surfaces the best content across all shows, all dates, all venues. Crowd energy. Stage production. Iconic moments. Organized by 
\f7\i what it feels like
\f0\i0  to be there, not by 
\f7\i which specific night it happened.
\f0\i0  This is what the London kid browses. This is the virtual attendance experience. This is also your SEO surface \'97 "Taylor Swift concert experience" has far more search volume than "Taylor Swift MSG June 14."\

\f2\b The archive view
\f0\b0  \'97 "Taylor Swift, Madison Square Garden, June 14" \'97 is the specific show page for people who were there and want to find their clips, or for the superfan who knows exactly which night she played a surprise song and wants to find footage of that specific moment. This is Concert Archives territory, but done properly.\
The key insight is that 
\f2\b the archive view generates the data, and the experience view surfaces the best of it.
\f0\b0  You don't have to choose. The upload always attaches to a specific event \'97 that's how the data gets organized. But the default browsing experience for a casual fan doesn't need to care about that granularity.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 What this means for the product\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 On the entity page
\f0\b0  \'97 the Taylor Swift page \'97 the default view isn't a chronological list of 152 tour dates. It's a curated 
\f2\b highlights reel
\f0\b0 : best videos, most-watched moments, iconic clips, surfaced across all shows. The date and venue are metadata, not the headline. The London kid lands here and immediately sees 20 incredible clips from Taylor Swift concerts. She doesn't need to pick a show first.\

\f2\b The show-specific view still exists
\f0\b0  \'97 but it's one level deeper. Fans who attended a specific night navigate there to find their show. Superfans who want to compare night 1 vs night 2 go there. The archive is real and valuable. It just isn't the front door.\

\f2\b The setlist-per-song granularity
\f0\b0  \'97 which we spent a lot of time on \'97 is probably a Phase 2 or power-user feature, not the core. For the London kid, "here are 40 clips of Cruel Summer from various shows" is more useful than "here are 6 clips of Cruel Summer from Atlanta night 1." The song-level tagging is still worth doing because it enables filtering, but the default shouldn't require that level of specificity to have a great experience.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 The analogy that makes this click\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Think about how Netflix presents a TV show. The show page has a highlights trailer that gives you the feel of the whole series. You don't have to pick Season 2 Episode 7 to decide if you want to watch it. But Season 2 Episode 7 exists and is exactly where you go once you're invested.\
Your entity page is the trailer. The specific show pages are the episodes. Most visitors never need to go deeper than the trailer. The people who do are your most engaged users \'97 and they'll love you for having the granularity.\
The archive angle doesn't disappear. It becomes the foundation that makes the experience view possible. Every specific upload feeds the machine. The casual viewer just never has to see the machine.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

